g_ref);\n      $finish;\n    end\n  end\n\n  // Simulation end check\n  initial begin\n    #(1000000);\n    $display("SIMULATION PASSED");\n    $finish;\n  end\n\nendmodule\n\n</testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe module interface is given below:\n<module_interface>\nmodule TopModule (input clk, input resetn, input [2:0] r, output logic [2:0] g);\n</module_interface>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The solution involves creating a state machine with states A, B, C as described in the state diagram. The state transitions depend on the current state and the input r. All state transitions are handled using always blocks. The outputs g are assigned based on the current state. The reset is active-low (resetn), and when active, the state is set to A. The state encoding can be done using a localparam with binary values. Since the problem mentions assigning any state codes, I used binary codes. For example, state A is 3\'b000, B as 3\'b001, C as 3\'b010. Wait, but the state variables can be defined with just enough bits. Wait, there are three states (A, B, C), so 2 bits would suffice. Wait, the outputs g are three bits, each corresponding to a state. For example, in state B, g is 3\'b100 (g0=1). Let me recheck the original state diagram details. In state A, if transitions occur based on r bits. The outputs for each state are: A has no outputs (all zeros?), but in state B, g0 is 1, state C g1 is 1. Wait, the original description says: B (g0=1), C (g1=1). So, the outputs are 3 bits: g0 is the first bit (g[0]), g1 is g[1], g2 is g[2]. So in state B, g is 3\'b100 (binary), in C it\'s 3\'b010. Wait, wait. If g0 is the first output, then g[0] corresponds to g0. For example: when in state B (g0=1), g would be 3\'b100 (if g0 is the first bit). Wait, but the way the state 